# Absence of, or a violation of, symmetry

This article is about the absence of [symmetry](/Symmetry). For a specific use in [mathematics](/Mathematics), see [asymmetric relation](/Asymmetric_relation). For other uses, see [Asymmetry (disambiguation)](/Asymmetry_(disambiguation)).

This article needs additional citations for [verification](/Wikipedia:Verifiability). Please help [improve this article](/Special:EditPage/Asymmetry) by [adding citations to reliable sources](/Help:Referencing_for_beginners). Unsourced material may be challenged and removed.
Find sources: &#160;"Asymmetry"&#160;–&#160;[news](https://www.google.com/search?as_eq=wikipedia&q=%22Asymmetry%22&tbm=nws)&#160; · [newspapers](https://www.google.com/search?as_eq=wikipedia&q=%22Asymmetry%22&tbm=nws&source=lnt&tbs=ar:1)&#160; · [books](https://www.google.com/search?tbs=bks:1&q=%22Asymmetry%22)&#160; · [scholar](https://scholar.google.com/scholar?q=%22Asymmetry%22)&#160; · [JSTOR](https://www.jstor.org/action/doBasicSearch?Query=%22Asymmetry%22&acc=on&wc=on) (May 2011) ( [Learn how and when to remove this message](/Help:Maintenance_template_removal) )

In the grand scheme of things, from the intricate dance of [geometry](/Geometry) to the chaotic ballet of physical processes, [asymmetry](/Asymmetry) simply refers to the noticeable lack or outright violation of [symmetry](/Symmetry). It's when some expected transformation—like a reflection in a mirror, or a rotation in space—doesn't leave an object or process looking precisely as it started, resulting in an unequivocally [observable difference](/Definition_of_ASYMMETRY). &#91;1&#93; [Symmetry](/Symmetry) itself is often touted as a fundamental property, admired in both the tangible structures we build and the abstract systems we concoct, sometimes defined with rigorous mathematical precision, other times merely appreciated in more nebulous, aesthetic terms. &#91;2&#93; Yet, it is precisely this absence, this defiance of an anticipated or desired [symmetry](/Symmetry), that can unleash profound and often inconvenient consequences upon a given system, revealing its true nature or, more often, its inherent imperfections.

## In organisms

Given the rather unglamorous mechanics of [cell division](/Cell_division) within [organisms](/Organism), it's hardly surprising that [asymmetry](/Asymmetry) is a fairly standard feature, manifesting in at least one dimension. While [biological symmetry](/Symmetry_in_biology) also makes its predictable appearance in other aspects, the universe, it seems, has a preference for the slightly off-kilter.

The venerable [Louis Pasteur](/Louis_Pasteur), with a foresight that might have been considered audacious in his era, once posited that [biological molecules](/Biological_molecule) inherently possess [asymmetry](/Asymmetry) because the very [cosmic](/Cosmos) (which is to say, [physical](/Physics)) forces overseeing their genesis are themselves fundamentally [asymmetric](/Asymmetry). While his contemporaries, and indeed many even now, tend to fixate on the perceived [symmetries of physical processes](/Symmetry_in_physics), it has since become clear that deeply fundamental [physical asymmetries](/Physical_asymmetry) exist. One need only consider the relentless, unidirectional march of [time](/Time) to grasp this rather obvious truth.

### Asymmetry in biology

*   Main articles: [Symmetry in biology](/Symmetry_in_biology) and [Left-right asymmetry (biology)](/Left-right_asymmetry_(biology))

[Asymmetry](/Asymmetry) isn't some rare anomaly; it's a pervasive and critically important characteristic that has, with typical evolutionary pragmatism, emerged countless times across a vast spectrum of [organisms](/Organism) and at myriad levels of [biological organization](/Biological_organization). This ranges from the microscopic intricacies of [individual cells](/Cell_(biology)) and the specialized forms of [organs](/Organ_(biology)) to the overarching [body-shapes](/Body_plan) of entire creatures. The advantages conferred by [asymmetry](/Asymmetry) often boil down to improved spatial arrangements—a more efficient packing, if you will. A classic example is the [human](/Human) [left lung](/Lung), which, with its slightly smaller size and one fewer [lobe](/Pulmonary_lobe) compared to its right counterpart, conveniently makes space for the equally [asymmetrical heart](/Heart) to nestle comfortably.

In other instances, the sheer efficiency of dividing functions between the left and right halves of an organism has proven so beneficial that it has actively driven the intensification of [asymmetry](/Asymmetry). This explanation is frequently invoked to account for [mammalian handedness](/Handedness), whether it's the preference of a [human](/Human) for their right hand or a [canine](/Canine) for a particular paw. The hypothesis suggests that dedicating the development of neural pathways to a skill primarily with one hand (or paw) might demand less effort and energy than attempting to achieve the same level of proficiency with both, a testament to the universe's inherent laziness, or perhaps, efficiency. &#91;3&#93;

Nature, in its infinite capacity to surprise (or perhaps, to simply adhere to the path of least resistance), provides numerous striking examples of [handedness](/Handedness) in traits that, at first glance, might appear to be [symmetrical](/Symmetry). Here are a few instances of [animals](/Animal) displaying pronounced [left-right asymmetries](/Left-right_asymmetry_(biology)):

*   Most [snails](/Snail), thanks to the fascinating and somewhat grotesque process of [torsion](/Torsion_(gastropod)) during their larval development, exhibit remarkable [asymmetry](/Asymmetry) not only in the elegant coil of their [shells](/Gastropod_shell) but also in the arrangement of their [internal organs](/Viscera). &#91;4&#93;
*   The male [fiddler crab](/Fiddler_crab), specifically species like *[Uca pugnax](/Uca_pugnax)*, presents a rather ostentatious display of [asymmetry](/Asymmetry) with one enormously oversized [claw](/Chela) and one noticeably diminutive one, primarily used for display and combat. &#91;5&#93;
*   The [narwhal](/Narwhal)'s iconic [tusk](/Tusk) is, in fact, an elongated [left incisor](/Incisor) that can reach lengths of up to 10 feet, forming a distinctive [left-handed helix](/Helix). &#91;6&#93;
*   [Flatfish](/Flatfish), having undergone a truly bizarre evolutionary journey, have adapted to swim with one side consistently facing upwards. The consequence? Both of their [eyes](/Eye) migrate to that single, upward-facing side of their heads, creating a truly unique and unequivocally [asymmetrical](/Asymmetry) cranial structure. &#91;7&#93;
*   Several species of [owls](/Owl) possess notable [asymmetries](/Asymmetry) in the size and precise positioning of their [ears](/Ear). This specialized arrangement is believed to be a crucial adaptation that significantly enhances their ability to precisely pinpoint the location of unsuspecting [prey](/Prey) in three-dimensional space, especially in low-light conditions. &#91;8&#93;
*   It turns out many [animals](/Animal) – from the smallest [insects](/Insect) to the largest [mammals](/Mammal) – sport [asymmetric male genitalia](/Genitalia). The precise evolutionary impetus behind this widespread anatomical quirk remains, in most cases, a rather persistent [mystery](/Mystery), much to the chagrin of biologists who prefer neat explanations. &#91;9&#93;

### As an indicator of unfitness

Of course, [asymmetry](/Asymmetry) isn't always a clever evolutionary trick. Sometimes, it's merely a glaring flaw, a biological red flag waving in the face of perceived perfection.

*   Certain disruptions occurring during the delicate developmental stages of an [organism](/Organism) can lead to [birth defects](/Birth_defect), which frequently manifest as pronounced [asymmetries](/Asymmetry). These are, quite frankly, undesirable.
*   Injuries sustained *after* the crucial stages of [cell division](/Cell_division) that cannot be adequately repaired by the [organism's biological mechanisms](/Biological_mechanism)—such as the unfortunate loss of a [limb](/Limb_(anatomy)) due to an accident—also create undeniable [asymmetries](/Asymmetry).

Given that both [birth defects](/Birth_defect) and significant [injuries](/Injury) tend to be rather strong indicators of an [organism's](/Organism) compromised health or general misfortune, defects that result in [asymmetry](/Asymmetry) frequently place an [animal](/Animal) at a distinct disadvantage, particularly when it comes to the highly competitive and often superficial arena of [mate finding](/Mate_choice). For instance, a higher degree of [facial symmetry](/Facial_symmetry) is universally (and somewhat predictably) perceived as more attractive in [humans](/Human), especially within the context of [mate selection](/Mate_selection). More broadly, a discernible [correlation](/Correlation_and_dependence) exists between [symmetry](/Symmetry) and various [fitness-related traits](/Fitness_(biology))—such as [growth rate](/Growth_rate), [fecundity](/Fecundity), and sheer [survivability](/Survivability)—across a multitude of [species](/Species). This implies that, through the relentless pressures of [sexual selection](/Sexual_selection), individuals who exhibit greater [symmetry](/Symmetry) (and are therefore often considered "fitter") tend to be preferred as mates, as they are statistically more likely to produce healthy, viable offspring. A rather brutal, yet effective, cosmic judgment. &#91;10&#93;

## In structures

For centuries, the pre-modern architectural world clung to a rather rigid emphasis on [symmetry](/Symmetry). It was the classical ideal, the expected norm, only truly deviated from when extreme site constraints or unforeseen historical developments forced a departure from this aesthetically pleasing, if somewhat predictable, convention. In stark contrast, the architects of [modernism](/Modern_architecture) and later [postmodernism](/Postmodernism) finally granted themselves the freedom to embrace [asymmetry](/Asymmetry) not as a flaw, but as a deliberate and powerful design element, a refreshing rejection of the perfectly balanced, the utterly expected.

While the vast majority of [bridges](/Bridge) naturally lean towards a [symmetrical form](/Symmetry) – primarily due to the inherent simplicities this offers in terms of design, structural analysis, fabrication, and the economical use of materials – a notable number of contemporary [bridges](/Bridge) have consciously broken away from this tradition. This departure is either a pragmatic response to highly specific site considerations (because the world rarely presents perfectly symmetrical problems) or a bold, deliberate artistic statement, a dramatic declaration of design intent.

