## In fire protection

In the rather crucial (and often overlooked) realm of [fire-resistance rated wall assemblies](/Fire-resistance_rating), which are integral components of [passive fire protection](/Passive_fire_protection) systems—including, but certainly not limited to, the formidable [fire barriers](/High-voltage_transformer_fire_barriers) surrounding [high-voltage transformers](/High-voltage_transformer)—[asymmetry](/Asymmetry) emerges as an absolutely critical aspect of design. When meticulously planning a facility, it is, regrettably, never entirely certain from which direction a potential [fire](/Fire) may originate. Consequently, many established [building codes](/Building_code) and rigorous [fire test standards](/Fire_test) explicitly stipulate that a [symmetrical assembly](/Symmetry), by its very nature, only requires testing from one side, given that both sides are, by definition, identical. However, the moment an assembly deviates into [asymmetry](/Asymmetry), the rules change with unforgiving precision: *both* sides must be subjected to testing, and the resulting [test report](/Test_report) is mandated to clearly state the performance outcomes for each individual side. In practical application, the lowest result achieved across these two tests is the one that ultimately appears in the official [certification listings](/Certification_listing). Neither the test sponsor, nor the laboratory conducting the evaluation, is permitted to rely on mere opinion or speculative deduction regarding which side might have been subjected to greater peril during a hypothetical fire. Both sides *must* be tested to ensure full compliance with the relevant [test standards](/Test_standard) and stringent [building codes](/Building_code). It’s a tedious, but necessary, concession to reality.

## In mathematics

*   See also: [Symmetry in mathematics](/Symmetry_in_mathematics)
*   This section needs expansion. You can help by adding to it. (July 2023)
    *   *Indeed. Because who doesn't love more abstract concepts to ponder.*

In the pristine, unforgiving world of [mathematics](/Mathematics), [asymmetry](/Asymmetry) can manifest in a multitude of forms, each as precise and undeniable as the last. Examples abound, from the strict conditions of [asymmetric relations](/Asymmetric_relation) to the stark visual disbalance of [asymmetry of shapes in geometry](/Geometry), and the intricate structures of [asymmetric graphs](/Asymmetric_graph), among other things.

In [geometry](/Geometry), a figure earns the label "asymmetric" if it possesses absolutely no form of [reflectional](/Reflection_symmetry), [rotational](/Rotational_symmetry), or [translational symmetry](/Translational_symmetry). Consider the humble [scalene triangle](/Scalene_triangle), a geometric outcast where every single side and every single angle defiantly differs from the others. It's the epitome of a lack of inherent balance. &#91;11&#93;

### Lines of symmetry

When attempting to ascertain whether an object is truly [asymmetrical](/Asymmetry), one typically begins by searching for its elusive [lines of symmetry](/Line_of_symmetry). A [square](/Square), for instance, boasts four distinct [lines of symmetry](/Line_of_symmetry), a rather impressive feat. A [circle](/Circle), in its boundless perfection, possesses an [infinite](/Infinity) number of such lines. The rule is deceptively simple: if a shape possesses *no* [lines of symmetry](/Line_of_symmetry) whatsoever, then it is, by definition, [asymmetrical](/Asymmetry). Conversely, if an object can claim even a single [line of symmetry](/Line_of_symmetry), it is, for all intents and purposes, considered [symmetrical](/Symmetry). Simple, yet often overlooked.

### Asymmetric Relation

An [asymmetric relation](/Asymmetric_relation) is a specific type of [binary relation](/Binary_relation), denoted as *R*, which is meticulously defined on a given set of elements. Its defining characteristic is this: if the condition *aRb* holds true for any two distinct elements, *a* and *b*, then it is an absolute necessity that the inverse condition, *bRa*, *must* be false. Stated with a touch more bluntness, an [asymmetric relation](/Asymmetric_relation) is fundamentally characterized by the indispensable absence of [symmetry](/Symmetry) when the relation is considered in the opposite direction.

[Inequalities](/Inequality_(mathematics)) serve as a rather straightforward illustration of [asymmetric relations](/Asymmetric_relation). Consider any two elements, *a* and *b*. If *a* is demonstrably less than *b* (expressed as *a < b*), then it is an undeniable truth that *a* cannot simultaneously be greater than *b* (i.e., *a ≯ b*). &#91;12&#93; This stark example clearly highlights how the relations "less than" and, by extension, "greater than" are intrinsically [asymmetric](/Asymmetry).

In direct contrast, if *a* is precisely equal to *b* (represented as *a = b*), then it naturally follows that *b* is also precisely equal to *a* (i.e., *b = a*). Thus, the binary relation "equal to" stands as a prime example of a [symmetric relation](/Symmetric_relation).

### Asymmetric Tensors

Generally speaking, an [asymmetric tensor](/Antisymmetric_tensor) is rigorously defined by the observable change in its sign (either a negative or positive inversion) when any two of its indices are interchanged. This property is crucial for understanding its behavior within various mathematical and physical contexts.

The [Epsilon-tensor](/Levi-Civita_symbol), often referred to as the [Levi-Civita symbol](/Levi-Civita_symbol), provides a quintessential example of an [asymmetric tensor](/Antisymmetric_tensor). It is formally defined as:

$$
\epsilon _{ijk}={\begin{cases}1&{\text{if }}(i,j,k)\in \{(123),(231),(312)\}\\-1&{\text{if }}(i,j,k)\in \{(213),(321),(132)\}\\0&{\text{else}}\end{cases}}
$$

where *i, j, k* are elements from the set {1, 2, 3}. &#91;13&#93; What this elegant definition demonstrates is that for [even permutations](/Permutations) of its indices, the tensor yields a value of 1, while for [uneven (or odd) permutations](/Permutations), it yields -1. Any repetition of indices, indicating a non-permutation, results in a value of 0. This intrinsic property of sign change upon index interchange is precisely what categorizes it as an [asymmetric tensor](/Antisymmetric_tensor), making it invaluable in areas like [vector calculus](/Vector_calculus) and [differential geometry](/Differential_geometry).

## In chemistry

*   This section needs expansion. You can help by adding to it. (July 2023)
    *   *One might think molecules would be simpler. They aren't.*

In the intricate world of [chemistry](/Chemistry), certain [molecules](/Molecule) possess a fascinating property known as [chirality](/Chirality_(chemistry)). This means they are, in essence, non-superimposable upon their own mirror images, much like your left hand cannot perfectly fit into a right-handed glove. Chemically identical [molecules](/Molecule) that differ solely in this spatial orientation are termed [enantiomers](/Enantiomer). This seemingly subtle difference in their three-dimensional arrangement can lead to profoundly divergent properties, particularly in the way they interact with complex [biological systems](/Biological_system), where a molecule's shape is often paramount to its function. For example, one [enantiomer](/Enantiomer) might be a life-saving drug, while its mirror image could be inert, or worse, toxic. The universe, it seems, cares about orientation.

## In physics

[Asymmetry](/Asymmetry) is not merely an occasional anomaly in [physics](/Physics); it arises, persistently and profoundly, across a multitude of different realms, often revealing deeper, more inconvenient truths about the fundamental nature of reality.

### Thermodynamics

The original, classical formulation of [thermodynamics](/Thermodynamics)—the one devoid of statistical probabilistic nuances—was, rather strikingly, [asymmetrical in time](/Entropy_(arrow_of_time)). It unequivocally asserted that the [entropy](/Entropy) within a truly [closed system](/Closed_system) could only ever increase as time marched forward, never decrease. This stark conclusion was rigorously derived from the [Second Law of Thermodynamics](/Second_law_of_thermodynamics) (either [Clausius](/Clausius)'s statement or [Lord Kelvin](/Lord_Kelvin)'s equivalent formulation could be employed) in conjunction with [Clausius's Theorem](/Clausius's_theorem) (a point eloquently elaborated upon by [Kerson Huang](/Kerson_Huang) in his seminal work, [ISBN](/ISBN_(identifier))&#160; 978-0471815181). However, the later, more nuanced theory of [statistical mechanics](/Statistical_mechanics), with its probabilistic underpinnings, presents a picture that is, in principle, [symmetric in time](/Time_symmetry). While it robustly predicts that a system significantly below its maximum [entropy](/Entropy) state is overwhelmingly likely to evolve towards higher [entropy](/Entropy), it also, rather unsettlingly, implies that such a system is equally likely to have evolved *from* a state of even higher [entropy](/Entropy). The cosmic arrow of time, then, is more of a statistical preference than an absolute decree.

### Particle physics

[Symmetry](/Symmetry_in_physics) stands as one of the most extraordinarily potent conceptual tools in the entire edifice of [particle physics](/Particle_physics). This is because it has become strikingly evident that virtually every fundamental [law of nature](/Physical_law) ultimately originates from some underlying [symmetry](/Symmetry). Consequently, observed violations of these cherished [symmetries](/Symmetry) do not represent mere imperfections; instead, they present profound theoretical and experimental puzzles that inevitably lead to a far deeper and more comprehensive understanding of nature's true mechanisms. Furthermore, [asymmetries](/Asymmetry) detected in experimental measurements often provide incredibly powerful handles—analytical footholds that are frequently relatively immune to confounding background noise or systematic uncertainties, allowing for clearer insights into the fundamental interactions.

#### Parity violation

*   Main article: [Parity (physics)](/Parity_(physics))

For decades leading up to the mid-1950s, it was a widely accepted dogma that the fundamental fabric of [physics](/Physics) was inherently [left-right symmetric](/Left-right_symmetry); that is to say, all fundamental [interactions](/Fundamental_interaction) were believed to be invariant under a spatial [parity transformation](/Parity_(physics)) (a mirror reflection). While [parity](/Parity_(physics)) is indeed meticulously conserved in [electromagnetism](/Electromagnetism), the [strong interactions](/Strong_interactions), and [gravity](/Gravity), it was stunningly discovered that it is, in fact, violated in the enigmatic [weak interactions](/Weak_interactions). The reigning [Standard Model](/Standard_Model) of [particle physics](/Particle_physics) elegantly incorporates this [parity violation](/Parity_violation) by describing the [weak interaction](/Weak_interaction) as a [chiral gauge interaction](/Chirality_(physics)). This means that, within the [Standard Model](/Standard_Model), only the [left-handed components](/Chirality_(physics)) of fundamental [particles](/Elementary_particle) and the [right-handed components](/Chirality_(physics)) of their corresponding [antiparticles](/Antiparticle) actively participate in the [weak interactions](/Weak_interaction). A profound consequence of this [parity violation](/Parity_violation) in [particle physics](/Particle_physics) is the rather peculiar observation that [neutrinos](/Neutrino) have only ever been detected as exclusively [left-handed particles](/Chirality_(physics)), while their [antiparticle](/Antiparticle) counterparts, [antineutrinos](/Antineutrino), are only observed as [right-handed particles](/Chirality_(physics)).

Between 1956 and 1957, the pioneering work of [Chien-Shiung Wu](/Chien-Shiung_Wu), E. Ambler, R. W. Hayward, D. D. Hoppes, and R. P. Hudson finally provided irrefutable evidence of a clear violation of [parity conservation](/Parity_conservation) during the [beta decay](/Beta_decay) of [cobalt-60](/Cobalt-60). &#91;[citation needed](/Wikipedia:Citation_needed)&#93; Almost simultaneously, and with remarkable speed, [R. L. Garwin](/Richard_Garwin), [Leon Lederman](/Leon_Lederman), and R. Weinrich ingeniously adapted an existing [cyclotron](/Cyclotron) experiment and immediately corroborated the phenomenon of [parity violation](/Parity_violation), cementing its place as a fundamental aspect of nature. &#91;[citation needed](/Wikipedia:Citation_needed)&#93;

#### CP violation

*   Main article: [CP-violation](/CP-violation)

Following the earth-shattering discovery of [parity violation](/Parity_violation) in 1956–57, the physics community, ever optimistic, largely believed that a combined [symmetry](/Symmetry)—that of [parity](/Parity_(physics)) (P) and simultaneous [charge conjugation](/Charge_conjugation) (C), collectively known as [CP](/CP-violation)—was steadfastly preserved. For instance, [CP symmetry](/CP-symmetry) would transform a [left-handed neutrino](/Neutrino) into a [right-handed antineutrino](/Antineutrino), maintaining a sort of balanced cosmic books. However, in 1964, [James Cronin](/James_Cronin) and [Val Fitch](/Val_Fitch) delivered yet another inconvenient truth, providing clear experimental evidence that [CP symmetry](/CP-symmetry) was also violated, observed in their groundbreaking experiment with neutral [kaons](/Kaon).

This [CP violation](/CP-violation) is not just a curious anomaly; it is, in fact, one of the absolutely necessary conditions for the very generation of the profound [baryon asymmetry](/Baryon_asymmetry) that characterizes our [early universe](/Early_universe). Without it, the universe as we know it simply wouldn't exist.

The final frontier of these combined [symmetries](/Symmetry) involves combining [CP symmetry](/CP-symmetry) with simultaneous [time reversal](/T-symmetry) (T), resulting in the ultimate combined [symmetry](/Symmetry) known as [CPT symmetry](/CPT_symmetry). The [CPT theorem](/CPT_theorem) dictates that [CPT symmetry](/CPT_symmetry) *must* be preserved in any [Lorentz invariant](/Lorentz_invariant) [local quantum field theory](/Quantum_field_theory) that operates with a [Hermitian](/Self-adjoint_operator) [Hamiltonian](/Hamiltonian_(quantum_mechanics)). As of 2006, despite persistent and rigorous experimental searches, no violations of [CPT symmetry](/CPT_symmetry) have ever been observed, suggesting it might be the one unwavering constant in a universe full of subtle imbalances.

#### Baryon asymmetry of the universe

*   Main article: [Baryogenesis](/Baryogenesis)

A rather stark and undeniable observation about the cosmos is that the [baryons](/Baryon) (that is, the [protons](/Proton) and [neutrons](/Neutron) that form the nuclei of [atoms](/Atom), and indeed the [atoms](/Atom) themselves) observed throughout the universe are overwhelmingly composed of [matter](/Matter), as opposed to [anti-matter](/Anti-matter). This profound and cosmological imbalance is precisely what is referred to as the [baryon asymmetry](/Baryon_asymmetry) of the universe. It's why we're here, instead of annihilating ourselves in a flash of gamma rays.

#### Isospin violation

[Isospin](/Isospin) represents a fundamental [symmetry transformation](/Symmetry_transformation) within the realm of the [strong interactions](/Strong_interactions). This conceptual framework was initially introduced by the brilliant [Werner Heisenberg](/Werner_Heisenberg) in the context of [nuclear physics](/Nuclear_physics), spurred by the empirical observations that the masses of the [neutron](/Neutron) and the [proton](/Proton) are remarkably similar, and that the sheer strength of the [strong interaction](/Strong_interaction) between any pair of [nucleons](/Nucleon) remains consistently the same, irrespective of whether they are [protons](/Proton) or [neutrons](/Neutron). This underlying [symmetry](/Symmetry) actually emerges at an even more fundamental level, manifesting as a [symmetry](/Symmetry) between [up-type](/Up_quark) and [down-type quarks](/Down_quark). [Isospin symmetry](/Isospin) in the [strong interactions](/Strong_interactions) can be conceptually broadened and considered a subset of a more expansive [flavor symmetry group](/Flavor_symmetry), within which the [strong interactions](/Strong_interactions) remain invariant under the interchange of different fundamental types of [quarks](/Quark). Integrating the [strange quark](/Strange_quark) into this intricate scheme gives rise to the elegant and predictive [Eightfold Way](/Eightfold_way_(physics)) classification system for both [mesons](/Meson) and [baryons](/Baryon).

However, even this theoretical elegance is not without its imperfections. [Isospin](/Isospin) is, regrettably, violated by the inconvenient fact that the masses of the [up](/Up_quark) and [down quarks](/Down_quark) are not precisely identical, and further, by their differing [electric charges](/Electric_charge). Because this violation represents only a relatively small effect in the vast majority of processes involving the [strong interactions](/Strong_interactions), [isospin symmetry](/Isospin) nevertheless remains an incredibly useful and powerful calculational tool, with its violations merely introducing calculable corrections to the results predicted by the ideal [isospin-symmetric](/Isospin) models. A practical compromise, if ever there was one.

### In collider experiments

Given that the [weak interactions](/Weak_interaction) fundamentally violate [parity](/Parity_(physics)), it is hardly surprising that [collider](/Collider) experiments, particularly those sensitive to these interactions, routinely exhibit discernible [asymmetries](/Asymmetry) in the spatial distributions of the resulting [final-state particles](/Final_state). These [asymmetries](/Asymmetry) are typically exquisitely sensitive to the subtle differences in the interaction strengths between [particles](/Particle) and [antiparticles](/Antiparticle), or between [left-handed](/Chirality_(physics)) and [right-handed particles](/Chirality_(physics)). Consequently, they serve as exceptionally powerful and sensitive tools for precisely measuring these interaction strength differences and, crucially, for distinguishing a faint, asymmetric signal from what might otherwise be an overwhelmingly large, yet symmetrical, background.

*   A [forward-backward asymmetry](/Forward-backward_asymmetry) is rigorously defined as A FB =(N F -N B )/(N F +N B ). Here, N F represents the total number of events in which a specific [final-state particle](/Final_state) is observed to be moving "forward" with respect to a carefully chosen reference direction (for example, a [final-state electron](/Electron) moving in the same general direction as the initial [electron beam](/Electron_beam) in [electron-positron collisions](/Electron-positron_annihilation)). Conversely, N B denotes the number of events where that very same [final-state particle](/Final_state) is observed moving "backward." [Forward-backward asymmetries](/Forward-backward_asymmetry) were famously employed by the [LEP](/LEP) experiments to precisely measure the difference in the interaction strength of the [Z boson](/Z_boson) between [left-handed](/Chirality_(physics)) and [right-handed fermions](/Fermion), providing an incredibly accurate determination of the [weak mixing angle](/Weak_mixing_angle).

*   A [left-right asymmetry](/Left-right_asymmetry_(biology)) is defined as A LR =(N L -N R )/(N L +N R ). In this formulation, N L represents the number of events where some [initial](/Initial_state)- or [final-state particle](/Final_state) is found to be [left-polarized](/Polarization_(waves)), while N R corresponds to the number of events with the particle being [right-polarized](/Polarization_(waves)). [Left-right asymmetries](/Left-right_asymmetry_(biology)) in [Z boson](/Z_boson) production and subsequent decay were meticulously measured at the [Stanford Linear Collider](/Stanford_Linear_Collider) by comparing the event rates obtained with [left-polarized](/Polarization_(waves)) versus [right-polarized](/Polarization_(waves)) initial [electron beams](/Electron_beam). These [left-right asymmetries](/Left-right_asymmetry_(biology)) can also be formulated in terms of [asymmetries](/Asymmetry) in the [polarization](/Polarization_(waves)) of [final-state particles](/Final_state) whose [polarizations](/Polarization_(waves)) can be directly measured; a prime example being the [tau leptons](/Tau_lepton).

*   A [charge asymmetry](/Charge_asymmetry) or, more specifically, a [particle-antiparticle asymmetry](/Particle-antiparticle_asymmetry), is defined in a conceptually similar fashion. This particular type of [asymmetry](/Asymmetry) has proven invaluable in constraining the [parton distribution functions](/Parton_(particle_physics)) of [protons](/Proton) at the [Tevatron](/Tevatron) using events where a produced [W boson](/W_boson) subsequently decays into a [charged lepton](/Lepton). The [asymmetry](/Asymmetry) observed between positively and negatively [charged leptons](/Lepton) as a function of the [W boson's](/W_boson) direction relative to the [proton beam](/Proton_beam) provides critical information regarding the relative distributions of [up](/Up_quark) and [down quarks](/Down_quark) within the [proton](/Proton). Furthermore, [particle-antiparticle asymmetries](/Particle-antiparticle_asymmetry) are extensively utilized to extract crucial measurements of [CP violation](/CP-violation) from the production of [B mesons](/Meson) and their corresponding [anti-B mesons](/Meson) in the groundbreaking [BaBar](/BaBar_experiment) and [Belle](/Belle_experiment) experiments. It’s all rather precise, if you bother to look.

